<subSubSection id="83193F6575152A37E81E2FCDBECBBA80" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2742B1971434086E52DCCE189AE38E95" pageNumber="2">
The Neotropical electric fish genus 
<taxonomicName id="E173EC9175A2C3D684237DFB9273BDDA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus (Linnaeus 1758)</taxonomicName>
is substantially more diverse than was previously recognized. New methods of sampling, identifying, and collecting electric fishes have unveiled numerous species in previously unexplored habitats and regions (Crampton 1996a; Lundberg et al.1996; Crampton 1998; Albert &amp; Crampton 2001). Further, the use of new techniques for characterizing morphology, electric organ discharges, and genetic differences have demonstrated that much of what was once regarded as intraspecific variation represents interspecific differences (Campos-da-Paz &amp; Costa 1996; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 1998a; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 1998b; Albert et al. 1999; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 2000; Fernandes-Matioli et al. 2001; Albert &amp; Crampton 2001; Fernandes-Matioli &amp; Almeida-Toledo, 2001).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="01D528425F42F2170AC36B80E539FD7B" lastPageNumber="3" pageNumber="2">
<taxonomicName id="3ADCD0CD02208417ED112FC856344B63" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
species are aggressive nocturnal predators of fishes and other small aquatic animals, and most are territorial. The males of at least two 
<taxonomicName id="14977CEF0456AAF40C9DE058918A50BF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
species build and guard nests of foam and/or aquatic vegetation (Crampton &amp; Hopkins pers. obs.). The type species 
<taxonomicName id="320F897808221F452661D1FB02109D44" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">Gymnotus carapo</taxonomicName>
is reported to mouth brood its eggs and larvae (Kirschbaum &amp; Wieczorek 2002). 
<taxonomicName id="CD80C6DB653007B9745A1C3F6B939861" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
is the most geographically widespread of all gymnotiforms, extending from the 
<normalizedToken id="109BE5CE0917FC0335A12A7CDECF452B" originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Salado in the Pampas of Argentina (36°S) to the 
<normalizedToken id="2DB09000B40FE11EA1F1E776DC1C3634" originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
San 
<normalizedToken id="5ECE59E306D39BE30DA05091B9CB4E24" originalValue="Nicolás">Nicolas</normalizedToken>
of southeastern Chiapas, Mexico (18°N), and is present in the continental waters of all South and Middle American countries except Chile and Belize (Albert 2001). Prior to this report, 25 species names were available for 
<taxonomicName id="2FDAFA8A16BED6F643127D98A3402A34" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
, of which five were synonymized with the type species 
<taxonomicName id="B89A769A7D18590256976A17C5B55374" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
(Mago-Leccia 1994), and one with 
<taxonomicName id="ABAF2B52169AA84D79C90D517FBA93E6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:960361B6-04A3-4620-8652-4250EE5C9E8A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus coatesi La Monte 1935:1" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coatesi">G. coatesi</taxonomicName>
(Campos da Paz 2000). The geographical ranges of the currently valid 
<taxonomicName id="5F87E6A2E822F89F93528DBDA8630C72" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
species are summarized in Table 1. 
<taxonomicName id="3644795BDD9EA07EA02F9D21432CE8AA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
exhibits its greatest diversity in the western portion of the Amazon basin where 10 species are currently recognized. 
<taxonomicName id="0995706F582E92BA235E4A3C3596CD63" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:7C0439E9-4610-4E00-9082-E644403A1653" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus anguillaris Hoedeman 1962:55" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="anguillaris">Gymnotus anguillaris Hoedeman</taxonomicName>
is recognized here as distinct from 
<taxonomicName id="7F81E248C06F9951290CD50BD36C5F1F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:71F3A25A-999A-43FE-93D9-F3936F1178D5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus coropinae Hoedeman 1962:55" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coropinae">G. coropinae Hoedeman</taxonomicName>
with which it has been synonymized (Nijssen &amp; 
<normalizedToken id="6D2C7D3292084EA8A22C529456C97D51" originalValue="Isbrücker">Isbruecker</normalizedToken>
1968). Data for and comparisons to 
<taxonomicName id="AC8843D9956112131D882D5798CA0F72" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:71F3A25A-999A-43FE-93D9-F3936F1178D5" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus coropinae Hoedeman 1962:55" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="coropinae">G. coropinae</taxonomicName>
will be presented in a forthcoming redescription of this species (Crampton &amp; Albert unpubl. obs.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0A03A4D93C9374B32343CF449FF780E8" lastPageNumber="4" pageNumber="3">
Here we present evidence for the existence of seven new species of 
<taxonomicName id="2F20DA645887DBAEB7D1024AD95F48C2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
from examination of populations from throughout tropical South and Middle America. We describe these new taxa on the basis of unique color patterns and unique combinations of morphometric, meristic, and osteological features. We also redescribe the geographically widespread species 
<taxonomicName id="AF0BBEFF9B5154B0CB64D48211681A4C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
sensu stricto (
<taxonomicName id="9A1E844D9CB7D9C89AC80CDE81549B73" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
s.s.) and distinguish six allopatric populations of 
<taxonomicName id="3D59F8F155F0819846B87D7A8678BDFA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
s.s. by differences in the mean and modal values of morphometric and meristic traits. The original description of 
<taxonomicName id="F2D14A84499958D826A6C07CD82B188C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo (Linnaeus, 1758)</taxonomicName>
provides only enough information to identify specimens to the Order Gymnotiformes (sensu MagoLeccia, 1994). Subsequent diagnoses and keys (Ellis 1913; Hoedeman 1962; Mago-Leccia 1994; Albert &amp; Miller 1995) did not provide sufficient information to differentiate 
<taxonomicName id="280E70A0CCD5E2289BF72C855163DC9A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
s.s. from other member of the 
<taxonomicName id="FF68ADFB26AE79426AAD0DBBA30C460F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5F46381A-E70B-478D-9692-D0720712B71B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus carapo Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="carapo">G. carapo</taxonomicName>
species-group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3145D49E7AA01674DC927063840EA1DC" pageNumber="4">
The material basis of these descriptions is 781 museum lots of 
<taxonomicName id="12623A24B35C2F7333CA0A13340C4853" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
bearing more than 2700 specimens from 32 museums. This study is to our knowledge the most thorough alpha-level review of morphological variation in any gymnotiform genus to date. The existence of so many previously unrecognized and undescribed taxa within existing museum collections is due in part to the cryptic nature of phenotypic diversity in 
<taxonomicName id="E3F98919E2BDB28531E10E7465D22857" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
. These fishes possess few external visual cues for species recognition. The lack of appreciation for diversity in 
<taxonomicName id="D2F2DC67CBF658F7B847FC9BE67AC060" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8F927E13-DF20-4313-BF35-89BA8B7DE1CE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Gymnotidae" genus="Gymnotus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnotus Linnaeus 1758:246" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnotus</taxonomicName>
has been compounded by a lack of published accounts of intraspecific variation. We predict that similarly high levels of cryptic diversity may exist in other gymnotiform groups with geographic distributions well represented in museum collections (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="4AF2D1D48CEACDF2C748B1F59646A259" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:71161FC6-E04D-4A81-A298-4DDB7CB5F7E0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Hypopomidae" genus="Brachyhypopomus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Brachyhypopomus Mago-Leccia 1994:47" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Brachyhypopomus</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="826E809D9BC6669760704FC58827DF47" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:872C4DCC-61A5-4BE1-A04B-B4708D60C673" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rhamphichthyidae" genus="Gymnorhamphichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Gymnorhamphichthys Ellis 1912:423, 436" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Gymnorhamphichthys</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="64AC811F8DC2687B1165C0385D06F7CB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sternopygidae" genus="Eigenmannia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Eigenmannia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="3EB5728F5C1B1B6F2C3CE8112FB02E7B" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6F85136B-D848-4991-BCE1-D75B760B078E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Apteronotidae" genus="Sternarchorhynchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sternarchorhynchus Castelnau 1855:91, 95" order="Gymnotiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Sternarchorhynchus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
